**Simulating the Path of Light can allow for the creation of Realistic Images**  
This project was made in Unity, but the implementation of the shaders is written by me. A brute-force raytraced dragon needs per second:  
(2560 x 1440 pixels) X (100rays/pixels) X (870000triangle intersections/ray) X (max 5 reflections) X (60 frames/second) ＝ **9.6x1016** ray triangle intersections, each requiring several floating point operations. 

An RTX4070 Laptop can do a maximum of 1.5 x 10^13 FLOPS, so it can’t be done in a reasonable amount of time. However, if we drop the realtime requirement, we can layer each frame on top of the previous frame’s result. With this, 1 ray per pixel can make for a decent image.  Further, we can use a binary tree to divide up a model’s polygons in space (BVH), making search possible in the order of 20 checks (log2870000). With this, we get down to 2.2 x 10^10 intersections. At this level, it is now quite doable. There are still many optimizations to be done before this becomes a real-time raytracer, but we can get some pretty cool images without exploding the computer now. ***What I love about this project is that it uses simple and elegant math to render incredibly complex and realistic lighting.***
